\begin_layout Subsection
Allowing for deviations from the law-of-one-price in the IO-system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the IO-chapter, we have the following expressions for demand prices:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{d,s,t}^{IOy}=\left(1+\tau_{d,s,t}^{IOy}\right)P_{s,t}^{Y}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{d,s,t}^{IOm}=\left(1+\tau_{d,s,t}^{IOm}\right)P_{s,t}^{M}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These assume that all sectors have the same demand price before taxes irrespecti
ve of the buyer.
 We can deviate from this by using the following expression for the demand
 price:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{d,s,t}^{IOy}=\left(1+\tau_{d,s,t}^{IOy}\right)\left(1+j_{d,t}^{pIOy}-j_{s,t}^{pY}\right)P_{s,t}^{Y}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{d,s,t}^{IOm}=\left(1+\tau_{d,s,t}^{IOm}\right)\left(1+j_{d,t}^{pIOm}-j_{s,t}^{pM}\right)P_{s,t}^{M}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The terms 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{d,t}^{pIOy}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{d,t}^{pIOm}$
\end_inset

are meant to allow deviations from the law of one price and are exogenous
 to the model.
 By shocking 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{d,t}^{pIOy}$
\end_inset

, we shock the demand price for a demand component supplied by domestic
 production.
 The increase in the demand price is not sector-specific.
 The terms 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s,t}^{pY}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s,t}^{pM}$
\end_inset

are necessary to ensure that central IO identities still hold.
 To explain how we set 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s,t}^{pY}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s,t}^{pM}$
\end_inset

, we use domestic production as an example, but the exact same could have
 been done with imports.
 Define demand prices before taxes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{d,s,t}^{IOyx}=\left(1+j_{d,t}^{pIOy}-j_{s,t}^{pY}\right)P_{s,t}^{Y}\label{eq:pioy_eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following IO-identities must hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{d}P_{d,s,t}^{IOyx}Q_{d,s,t}^{IOy}=Y_{s,t}P_{s,t}^{Y}\label{eq:ident_1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{d}Q_{d,s,t}^{IOy}=Y_{s,t}\label{eq:ident_2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In absence of the term 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{d,t}^{pIOy}-j_{s,t}^{pY}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{d,s,t}^{IOyx}=P_{s,t}^{Y}$
\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ident_1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is identical to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ident_2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 But with 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{d,t}^{pIOy}-j_{s,t}^{pY}$
\end_inset

 this is no longer true.
 If we shock 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{d,s,t}^{pIOY}$
\end_inset

while setting 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s,t}^{pY}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ident_1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is violated since
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ident_2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 must still hold.
 We can derive a condition to set 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s,t}^{pY}$
\end_inset

 such that both conditions hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{d}P_{d,s,t}^{IOyx}q_{d,s,t}^{IOy}=\sum_{d}\left(1+j_{d,t}^{pIOy}-j_{s,t}^{pY}\right)P_{s,t}^{Y}q_{d,s,t}^{IOy}=Y_{s,t}P_{s,t}^{Y}\Longleftrightarrow Y_{s,t}=\sum_{d}\left(1+j_{d,t}^{pIOy}-j_{s,t}^{pY}\right)q_{d,s,t}^{IOy}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Longleftrightarrow\sum_{d}j_{d,t}^{pIOy}q_{d,s,t}^{IOy}=j_{s,t}^{pY}\sum_{d}q_{d,s,t}^{IOy}\Longleftrightarrow j_{s,t}^{pY}=\frac{\sum_{d}j_{d,t}^{pIOy}q_{d,s,t}^{IOy}}{Y_{s,t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equivalent condition for 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s,t}^{pM}$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
j_{s,t}^{pM}=\frac{\sum_{d}j_{d,t}^{pIOm}q_{d,s,t}^{IOm}}{M_{s,t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a shock to some demand component price through 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{d,t}^{pIOy}$
\end_inset

, we then move all other demand prices such that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ident_1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 holds.
 While not necessary, we would like the supply prices to move in conjunction
 with our shocks to the demand prices.
 This is achieved by simply adding 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s,t}^{pY}$
\end_inset

 to the markup in 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s,t}^{Y}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We do this by adding 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{s,t}^{pY}$
\end_inset

to the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s,t}^{Y}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{s,t}^{Y}=(1+\theta_{t}+j_{s,t}^{pY})P_{s,t}^{0}\label{eq:pY_eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Solving CES nests
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Solving CES nests"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In solving a CES nest you have a set of simple optimization problems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\underset{Q_{1},Q{}_{2}}{MIN}\left[P_{1}Q_{1}+P_{2}Q_{2}\right]\\
s.t.\\
Q=\left(\mu_{1}^{1/\sigma}Q{}_{1}^{\left(\sigma-1\right)/\sigma}+\mu_{2}^{1/\sigma}Q_{2}^{\left(\sigma-1\right)/\sigma}\right)^{\sigma/\left(\sigma-1\right)}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrange function is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\mathcal{L}=P_{1}Q_{1}+P_{2}Q_{2}-\lambda\left(\left(\mu_{1}^{1/\sigma}Q{}_{1}^{\left(\sigma-1\right)/\sigma}+\mu_{2}^{1/\sigma}Q_{2}^{\left(\sigma-1\right)/\sigma}\right)^{\sigma/\left(\sigma-1\right)}-Q\right)\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first order conditions are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial Q_{1}}=P_{1}-\lambda Q^{1/(\sigma-1)}\mu_{1}^{1/\sigma}Q{}_{1}^{-1/\sigma}\end{array}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial Q_{2}}=P_{2}-\lambda Q^{1/(\sigma-1)}\mu_{2}^{1/\sigma}Q{}_{2}^{-1/\sigma}\end{array}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\lambda}=Q-\left(\mu_{1}^{1/\sigma}Q{}_{1}^{\left(\sigma-1\right)/\sigma}+\mu_{2}^{1/\sigma}Q_{2}^{\left(\sigma-1\right)/\sigma}\right)^{\sigma/\left(\sigma-1\right)}\end{array}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first two FOC yields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\frac{Q_{1}}{Q_{2}}=\end{array}\frac{\mu_{1}}{\mu_{2}}\left(\frac{P_{1}}{P_{2}}\right)^{-\sigma}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Isolating Q1 and inserting in the third FOC yields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
Q_{2}=\mu_{2}Q\left(\frac{P_{2}}{\left(\mu_{1}P_{1}^{-\left(\sigma-1\right)}+\mu_{2}P_{2}^{-\left(\sigma-1\right)}\right)^{1/\left(\sigma-1\right)}}\right)^{-\sigma}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inserting this in the third FOC yields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
Q_{1}=\mu_{1}Q\left(\frac{P_{1}}{\left(\mu_{1}P_{1}^{-\left(\sigma-1\right)}+\mu_{2}P_{2}^{-\left(\sigma-1\right)}\right)^{1/\left(\sigma-1\right)}}\right)^{-\sigma}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total cost is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
PQ=P_{1}Q_{1}+P_{2}Q_{2}=\left(\mu_{1}P_{1}^{-\left(\sigma-1\right)}+\mu_{2}P_{2}^{-\left(\sigma-1\right)}\right)^{-1/\left(\sigma-1\right)}Q\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This yields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
P=\left(\mu_{1}P_{1}^{-\left(\sigma-1\right)}+\mu_{2}P_{2}^{-\left(\sigma-1\right)}\right)^{-1/\left(\sigma-1\right)}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inserting yields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
Q_{1}=\mu_{1}Q\left(\frac{P_{1}}{P}\right)^{-\sigma}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
Q_{2}=\mu_{2}Q\left(\frac{P_{2}}{P}\right)^{-\sigma}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


