\begin_layout Subsection
CES and Paasche price indices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CES demand for a quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 is (for i=1,2) derived in appendix 1.2 and given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
Q_{i,t}=\mu_{i,t}Q_{t}^{CES}\left(\frac{P_{i,t}}{P_{t}^{CES}}\right)^{-\sigma}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 is a share parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{t}^{CES}$
\end_inset

 is the CES aggregate of the demand components, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 is the the price for demand component i, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}^{CES}$
\end_inset

 is the CES price index and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the elasticity of substitution.
 The budget constraint gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
P_{t}^{CES}Q_{t}^{CES}=\sum_{i}P_{i,t}Q_{i,t}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above two equations implicitly gives the CES price index.
 In MAKRO all CES price indices are implicitly given.
 Inserting and writing the CES price index explicitly gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
P_{t}^{CES}=\left(\sum_{i}\mu_{i,t}P_{i,t}^{-\left(\sigma-1\right)}\right)^{-1/\left(\sigma-1\right)}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The national accounts use Laspeyres chain index for quantities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
P_{t-1}^{PCI}Q_{t}^{LCI}=\sum_{i}P_{i,t-1}Q_{i,t}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}^{PCI}$
\end_inset

 is a Paasche chain index for prices and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{t}^{LCI}$
\end_inset

 is a Laspeyres chain index for quantities.
 Together with the budget constraint this yields a Paasche chain index for
 prices:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
P_{t}^{PCI}=P_{t-1}^{PCI}\frac{\sum_{i}P_{i,t}Q_{i,t}}{\sum_{i}P_{i,t-1}Q_{i,t}}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For historical data the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 are calibrated so either 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}^{CES}=P_{t}^{PCI}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{t}^{CES}=Q_{t}^{LCI}$
\end_inset

 together with the budget constraint the one implies the other and we need
 not to distinguish.
 This implies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{i,t0}=\begin{array}{c}
\frac{Q_{i,t0}}{Q_{t0}^{LCI}}\left(\frac{P_{i,t0}}{P_{t0}^{PCI}}\right)^{\sigma}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

where t0 is the last year of the calibration period.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the forecast period our CES prices will only equal Paasche chain prices
 if:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
